column1367: 0); background-color: transparent; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\\\">Como todo MOOC
column1368: TIM Tec pode ser utilizado por muitas pessoas ao mesmo tempo. A plataforma é responsiva e leve: os vídeos ficam hospedados no Youtube
column1370: não é preciso ter um servidor pesado para assisti-los.
column1372: 0); background-color: transparent; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\\\">A ferramenta foi concebida desde a raiz para ser replicada e adotada por instituições de ensino. Ela possui diversas funcionalidades específicas para a gestão de estudantes. É possível criar turmas (cada curso pode ter sua própria divisão de turmas) e atribuir diferentes perfis para professores (professor coordenador e professor assistente). Para os educadores
column1373: fica fácil acompanhar o progresso dos estudantes
column1374: saber os cursos e atividades que cada um fez e inserir atividades novas e materiais adicionais além daqueles que já estão na plataforma. Além disso
column1375: os professores podem interagir direto com os alunos por meio de mensagem privada.
column1377: 0); background-color: transparent; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\\\">A plataforma permite gerar certificados de conclusão do curso e atestados de horas. TIM Tec fornece os esqueletos desses documentos
column1378: e os professores os complementam incluindo o logo da instituição de ensino
column1382: etc. Outra funcionalidade é que os cursos podem ser facilmente exportados e importados entre instituições. Dá para exportar um curso
column1383: gerando um pacote que mantém todas as configurações
column1384:
e enviá-lo para que outras instituições o utilizem nas suas instalações da plataforma TIM Tec.

Global WordPress Translation Day is a one-day contributor initiative organised by the WordPress project’s Polyglots team that is dedicated to helping new contributors who would like to translate WordPress in one of the 160 languages WordPress is available in.

\n

Global WordPress Translation Day will be on Sunday
column2989:
starting at 0:00 UTC and will go on for 24 hours covering all time zones.

What are we doing?

  • Live training: A 24h live streaming of tutorials about translating WordPress in different languages and making your code translatable (30min/1h sessions in different languages including a general instruction and specifics for that particular language). The internationalization sessions will be in English. The sessions will be presented by some of the most experienced WordPress translators and internationalization experts. The Schedule can be found on the website.
  • Local translation contributor days: Groups of contributors gather at different locations and work face to face.
  • Local remote translation contributor days: Current translation teams dedicate time and get involved remotely to do orientation for their potential contributors or work with their current translation teams on translating as many strings as they can.

If you organise a local meetup
column2990:
why not organise a contributor day for translating in your language?

Join us! Read about the initiative and sign up as an organiser.

Can I get involved if I only speak English?

Yes! Even if you only speak English
column2991: it would be great to get involved and check out some of the English locale variants – English as spoken in the United Kingdom
column2995: South Africa. English has many variants across the globe and you can learn about the differences and why it’s important that users have the option to choose a variant during some of our sessions. And if you’re in a funky mood
column2996: you can give translating the interface into Emoji a try! Yes
column2997:
we have a WordPress in Emoji locale!

Questions?

The polyglots team and the event organisers hang out in #Polyglots in Slack. They will gladly help you out.

The release candidate for WordPress 4.5 is now available.

\n

We’ve made 49 changes since releasing Beta 4 a week ago. RC means we think we’re done
column3003: but with millions of users and thousands of plugins and themes
column3004: it’s possible we’ve missed something. We hope to ship WordPress 4.5 on <strong>Tuesday
column3006:
but we need your help to get there.

\n

If you haven’t tested 4.5 yet
column3007:
now is the time!

\n

Think you’ve found a bug? Please post to the Alpha/Beta support forum. If any known issues come up
column3008:
you’ll be able to find them here.

\n

To test WordPress 4.5
column3009:
you can use the WordPress Beta Tester plugin or you can download the release candidate here (zip).

\n

For more information about what’s new in version 4.5
column3014: please test your plugins and themes against WordPress 4.5 and update your plugin’s Tested up to version in the readme to 4.5 before next week. If you find compatibility problems
column3015: we never want to break things
column3016:
so please be sure to post to the support forums so we can figure those out before the final release.

\n

Be sure to follow along the core development blog
column3017:
where we’ll continue to post notes for developers for 4.5.

Free as in Freedom
It is WordPress 4.5
Also free as in beer

WordPress 4.5 Beta 4 is now available!

\n

This software is still in development
column3021: so we don’t recommend you run it on a production site. Consider setting up a test site just to play with the new version. To test WordPress 4.5
column3022:
try the WordPress Beta Tester plugin (you’ll want “bleeding edge nightlies”). Or you can download the beta here (zip).

\n

For more information on what’s new in 4.5
column3026: along with in-depth field guides on make/core. This is the final planned beta of WordPress 4.5
column3027:
with a release candidate scheduled for next week.

Some of the changes in Beta 4 include:

  • Add support for oEmbed moments and timelines from Twitter (#36197).
  • More changes to better support HHVM with Imagick. Please test with HHVM setups and resizing/rotating images (#35973).
  • Tightened up the Inline Link feature (#33301
column3028:
#30468).\n
  • Support <hr> editor shortcut with 3 or more dashes (---); no spaces. To give more time to study the best shortcuts for users
column3029:
text patterns for bold and italic have been removed and won’t ship with for 4.5 (#33300).\n
  • Fixes for SSL with Responsive Images. Please test with SSL
column3030:
especially on sites with mixed http/https setups (#34945).
  • Allow rewrite rules to work in nested WordPress installations on IIS (#35558).
  • Various bug fixes. We’ve made almost 100 changes during the last week.

    • If you think you’ve found a bug
column3031: you can post to the Alpha/Beta area in the support forums. We’d love to hear from you! If you’re comfortable writing a reproducible bug report
column3032: file one on the WordPress Trac. There
column3033:
you can also find a list of known bugs.

Happy testing!

Llegamos al fin
del tiempo pa’ beta
¡Pruébalo Ahora!

WordPress 4.5 Beta 3 is now available!

\n

This software is still in development
column3037: so we don’t recommend you run it on a production site. Consider setting up a test site just to play with the new version. To test WordPress 4.5
column3038:
try the WordPress Beta Tester plugin (you’ll want “bleeding edge nightlies”). Or you can download the beta here (zip).

\n

For more information on what’s new in 4.5
column3039: check out the Beta 1 and Beta 2 blog posts
column3040:
along with in-depth field guides on make/core. Some of the fixes in Beta 3 include:

\n
    \n
  • Many Theme Logo Support (#33755) fixes
column3041:
including support for bundled Twenty Fifteen (#35944).
  • Add Responsive Preview to theme install previewer (#36017).
  • Support Imagick in HHVM (#35973).
  • Whitelist IPTC
column3043: and EXIF profiles from strip_meta() to maintain authorship
column3046:
and image orientation (#28634).\n
  • Support Windows shares/DFS roots in wp_normalize_path() (#35996).
    • \n
  • New installs default to generating secret keys and salts locally instead of relying on the WordPress.org API. Please test installing WP in situations where it can’t connect to the internet (like on a ?
column3048:
or ?) (#35290).
  • OPTIONS requests to REST API should return Allow header (#35975).
  • Upgrade twemoji.js to version 2 (#36059) and add extra IE11 compatibility (#35977) for Emoji.
  • Various bug fixes. We’ve made more than 100 changes during the last week.

    • If you think you’ve found a bug
column3049: you can post to the Alpha/Beta area in the support forums. We’d love to hear from you! If you’re comfortable writing a reproducible bug report
column3050: file one on the WordPress Trac. There
column3051:
you can also find a list of known bugs.

\n

Happy testing!

\n

three
\nso many bugs have been fixed
\nCloser now; four

WordPress 4.5 Beta 2 is now available!

\n

This software is still in development
column3058: so we don’t recommend you run it on a production site. Consider setting up a test site just to play with the new version. To test WordPress 4.5
column3059:
try the WordPress Beta Tester plugin (you’ll want “bleeding edge nightlies”). Or you can download the beta here (zip).

\n

For more information on what’s new in 4.5
column3060:
check out the Beta 1 blog post. Some of the fixes in Beta 2 include:

  • Added Horizontal Rule (HR) editing shortcut and dismissible “Paste as Text” notice in TinyMCE.
  • Selective Refresh support is enabled for core themes titles and taglines
column3061:
which allows shift-click to focus on controls and PHP filters to apply in the preview.
  • Resolved a fatal error on image upload when ImageMagick could not complete stripping meta during resize (#33642).
  • Various bug fixes. We’ve made just over 100 changes in the last week.

    • If you think you’ve found a bug
column3062: you can post to the Alpha/Beta area in the support forums. We’d love to hear from you! If you’re comfortable writing a reproducible bug report
column3063: file one on the WordPress Trac. There
column3064:
you can also find a list of known bugs.

Happy testing!

It’s peer pressure time
Testing: all cool kids do it
Help find ALL the bugs!

It’s time for our second global contributor weekend
column3070: and this time we’re focusing on the video team. For this month’s challenge
column3071: in honor of it being our second month
column3072: you have two options for how you can participate! The challenge for this month overall is to work with at least one hour worth of WordCamp video
column3073:
which you can do by either creating subtitles or editing the video file in preparation for upload to WordPress.tv.

\n

One of the great things about contributing to the video team is that you get to learn so much
column3074: since all the work basically involves watching WordCamp presentation videos. Subtitling is a doubly important need
column3075: as it is needed to make all those WordCamp videos accessible to people who are deaf or hard of hearing and can’t listen to the audio track
column3076:
as well as making it possible for the videos to be consumed (in some cases after subtitle translation) by people who speak different languages.

\n

The challenge will last from Saturday
column3081: and the results will be reviewed afterward by members of the video team. If you enjoy the challenge
column3082:
the video team would be very excited to welcome you into their ranks! Interested? Here’s how to participate.

\n

What About Last Month?

\n

In January
column3083: the inaugural contributor weekend was focused on the support forums. That challenge had 73 participants
column3084: including 10 people who provided 20 or more correct answers to open support threads
column3085: thereby winning the challenge. Congratulations to Harris Anastasiadis
column3094: and Sarah Semark! To them and to everyone else who participated
column3095: thank you so much for your efforts. Every answer helps
column3096: and over the course of this contributor weekend
column3097: these amazing volunteers responded to 800 support threads. The support forums queue of requests with no replies went from 28 pages to 7 pages — that was an incredible success
column3098:
of which every participant was a part!

\n

So head on over to see how to get involved with the one-hour video challenge this weekend
column3099:
and help us make next month’s post just as impressive!

WordPress 4.5 Beta 1 is now available!

\n

This software is still in development
column3103: so we don’t recommend you run it on a production site. Consider setting up a test site just to play with the new version. To test WordPress 4.5
column3104:
try the WordPress Beta Tester plugin (you’ll want “bleeding edge nightlies”). Or you can download the beta here (zip).

\n

WordPress 4.5 is slated for release on April 12
column3106: we need your help testing what we have been working on
column3107:
including:

\n
    \n
  • Responsive Preview of your site in the Customizer (#31195) – See how your site looks in mobile
column3109:
and desktop contexts before making changes to its appearance.\n
  • Theme Logo Support (#33755) – Native support for a theme logo within the Customizer.
    • \n
  • Inline Link Editing (#33301) – Within the visual editor
column3110:
edit links inline for a smoother workflow.\n
  • Additional Editor Shortcuts (#33300) – Includes a few new shortcuts
column3111:
like `..` for code and **..** for bold.\n
  • Comment Moderation Improvements (#34133) – An enhanced experience when moderating comments
column3112:
including preview with rendered formatting.\n
  • Optimization of Image Generation (#33642) – Image sizes are generated more efficiently and remove unneeded meta
column3113: while still including color profiles in Imagick
column3114:
for reduced sizes of up to 50% with near identical visual quality.

 

There have been changes for developers to explore as well:

  • Selective Refresh (#27355) – A comprehensive framework for rendering parts of the customizer preview in real time. Theme and plugin authors should test their widgets specifically for compatibility with selective refresh
column3115:
and note that it may ultimately be opt-in for 4.5.
  • Backbone and Underscore updated to latest versions (#34350) – Backbone is upgraded from 1.1.2 to 1.2.3 and Underscore is upgraded from 1.6.0 to 1.8.3. See the this post for important changes.
  • Embed templates (#34561) – Embed templates were split into parts and can now be directly overridden by themes via the template hierarchy.
  • New WP_Site class (#32450) – More object-oriented approach for managing sites in Multisite
  • Script loader (#14853
column3116: #35873) – Introduces wp_add_inline_script() for including inline JavaScript just like wp_add_inline_style() works for CSS
column3117:
and better support for script header/footer dependencies.\n\n

If you want a more in-depth view of what major changes have made it into 4.5
column3118: check out all 4.5-tagged posts on the main development blog
column3119:
or check out a list of everything that’s changed.

\n

If you think you’ve found a bug
column3120: you can post to the Alpha/Beta area in the support forums. We’d love to hear from you! If you’re comfortable writing a reproducible bug report
column3121: file one on the WordPress Trac. There
column3122:
you can also find a list of known bugs.

Happy testing!

A wonderful day
is one that brings new WordPress

WordCamps are locally-organized WordPress conferences that happen all over the world (and are so fun). Sometimes people don’t realize that WordCamps are organized by local volunteers rather than a central organization
column3129: “Can you bring WordCamp to my city?” When this happens
column3130: we always suggest they start with a meetup group
column3131: and think about organizing a WordCamp themselves after their group has been active for a few months. We emphasize that WordCamps are locally-organized events
column3132:
not something that the central community team plans from afar.

\n

This has been successful in many areas — there are currently 241 meetup groups on our meetup.com chapter program! In some regions
column3134: enthusiastic volunteers have had more of a challenge getting things started. Because of this
column3135:
we’re going to try an experiment this year called the WordCamp Incubator.

\n

The intention of the incubator program is to help spread WordPress to underserved areas through providing more significant organizing support for a first event. In practical terms
column3136: this experiment means we’ll be choosing three cities in 2016 where there is not an active WordPress community — but where it seems like there is a lot of potential and where there are some people excited to become organizers — and will help to organize their first WordCamp. These WordCamps will be small
column3138:
one-track events geared toward the goal of generating interest and getting people involved in creating an ongoing local community.*

\n

So
column3139: where should we do these three events?  If you have always wanted a WordCamp in your city but haven’t been able to get a meetup group going
column3140: this is a great opportunity. We will be taking applications for the next week
column3141:
then will get in touch with everyone who applied to discuss the possibilities. We will announce the  cities chosen by the end of March.

\n

To apply
column3143: 2016. You don’t need to have any specific information handy
column3144: it’s just a form to let us know you’re interested. You can apply to nominate your city even if you don’t want to be the main organizer
column3145: but for this experiment  we will need local liaisons and volunteers
column3146:
so please only nominate cities where you live or work so that we have at least one local connection to begin.

\n

Thanks
column3148: that describes the ideal first WordCamp even if you have an active meetup — there’s no need to wait until your group is big enough to support a large multi-day event
column3149:
and small events are a lot of fun because everyone has a chance to be involved and get to know most of the other attendees.

WordPress 4.4.2 is now available. This is a security release for all previous versions and we strongly encourage you to update your sites immediately.

\n

WordPress versions 4.4.1 and earlier are affected by two security issues: a possible SSRF for certain local URIs
column3153: reported by Ronni Skansing; and an open redirection attack
column3154:
reported by Shailesh Suthar.

\n

Thank you to both reporters for practicing responsible disclosure.

\n

In addition to the security issues above
column3155: WordPress 4.4.2 fixes 17 bugs from 4.4 and 4.4.1. For more information
column3156:
see the release notes or consult the list of changes.

Download WordPress 4.4.2 or venture over to Dashboard → Updates and simply click “Update Now.” Sites that support automatic background updates are already beginning to update to WordPress 4.4.2.

Thanks to everyone who contributed to 4.4.2:

Andrea Fercia

Our first global contributor drive is coming up next weekend
column3175:
and we want you to be involved!

\n

Many of our current contributors first got involved at a Contributor Day at a WordCamp or WordPress Meetup event near them
column3176: but not everyone has had that opportunity
column3177: so we’re trying to create an online experience that will give new contributors the same kind of live support and group dynamic. We’ll be doing these as weekend challenges rather than one-day events so that WordPress users all over the world can participate without worrying about pesky time zones
column3178: but each challenge will be designed to be completed within a few hours
column3179:
comparable to an in-person Contributor Day.

\n

Our inaugural Contributor Weekend is focused on the Support Team — the folks who volunteer their time to help people with WordPress questions in the support forums and IRC. Over the two day span
column3180:
forum moderators will be available online to help new contributors and answer questions as needed. The challenge this month is called 20 Questions; your mission (should you choose to accept it) is to help WordPress users by answering 20 forum support requests over the course of the weekend.

\n

You can participate on your own
column3181: or you can get together with other people from your local meetup group and work on it together. Working together in person is really fun
column3182: so we highly recommend trying to get some folks together if you’re able
column3183: but if that’s not possible you can still connect to other participants online. Either way
column3184:
this is a great way to give back to the WordPress project and have some fun helping people at the same time.

Interested? Get the details on how to participate.

Hope to see you next weekend!

Back in March
column3203: I explained how to connect WordPress powers sites to Apple News. After three weeks of being in the system
column3204:
here is what I experienced.

\n

Stuck in Limbo

\n

After configuring the plugin and successfully getting WP Tavern approved on Apple News
column3205: I thought that articles published on the site would automatically publish to Apple News. It didn’t work out that way
column3207:
not at first.

\n

When checking the status of those articles in the WordPress backend
column3208:
the Publish to Apple News plugin listed articles as Pending. Apple’s News publisher also didn’t show any drafts from WordPress or published articles.

\n

Based on some Google searches
column3209: I created and published a new article within the Apple News Publisher app. Unfortunately
column3210: it didn’t show up as a published article and because it was the first one
column3211:
it had to be approved by Apple News.

\nApple News Publisher First Submission\n

The first article published in Apple News was on March 21st. Between March 21st and March 31st
column3212:
I was stuck in limbo. I had no idea when the article would be approved or at what point in the process I was in.

\n

With the lack of communication
column3213: I started troubleshooting the Publish to Apple News plugin thinking that something was wrong. In the plugin’s settings
column3214: there’s an option to turn debugging on which sends emails to a specified email address each time an article is published
column3216:
or deleted with a detailed API response.

\nApple News Publisher Debug Options\n

I didn’t receive any emails when articles were published leading me to believe there was a potential communication issue between the Tavern and Apple News. A few days passed by when all of a sudden
column3217:
I received two emails with debug information.

\n

I checked the Tavern’s Apple News channel and discovered that the first article I published using Apple’s publishing tool was approved. Had I not checked the channel
column3218:
I wouldn’t have known that it was approved. I disabled debug mode in the Publish to Apple News plugin and noticed articles published on the Tavern after the approval appeared as expected.

Published Articles In Apples News Publisher

Apple should send an email notification when the first article is approved along with details that future articles will be published automatically.

What Articles Look Like in the Apple News App

I kept the default style settings provided by the Publish to Apple News plugin. As you can see
column3219: the articles don’t look that bad with the exception of the WordCamp Central article. For some reason
column3220:
the image splits up the first sentence of the post. I’m looking into why this happens but I’ve seen it on other posts as well.

One thing I don’t like is that if an image is used at the beginning of an article
column3221:
the Apple News App displays the HTML code of the image on the article listing page instead of article text. It would be more beneficial to readers if the listing page displayed text from the article and not HTML related to images.

\n

Apple News Publisher Analytics

\n

According to the analytics dashboard in Apple News Publisher
column3222: some of you have subscribed to our channel. The dashboard includes stats like
column3226:
and more.

\nApple News Analytics\n

You can even dive into analytics on a per post level to determine why some articles do better than others. To view stats in a different program or to back them up
column3227:
Apple News publisher allows you to download up to 30 days worth of data at once in CSV format.

\n

The Experiment Continues

\n

There’s not enough data to determine if publishing articles to Apple News is worth the effort. Three months from now
column3228:
I’ll look at the data and publish a follow-up post with our findings. It will also include reviews from readers who are subscribed to our channel to find out what they like and dislike about consuming WP Tavern’s content through Apple News.

\n

Although the process could use some improvement
column3230: once the approval process is complete
column3231:
the system runs automatically. Let us know in the comments what your experience has been like connecting your site to Apple News Publisher.

\n

Williamson
column3233: who is known for his yearly transparency reports
column3234: shared that AffiliateWP was the fastest of his products to reach $100
column3235: 000 in annual revenue. It took just nine months for the plugin to reach that goal and in 2015 it passed $30
column3236:
000 in monthly revenue.

\n

“Our first month to break $30
column3242: we have had only 3 months that were below 30
column3243:
and they were only just barely below the 30 mark.”

\n

They say that necessity is the mother of invention
column3244: and this was certainly the case with the creation of AffiliateWP. Williamson said that his customers were always asking for recommendations on affiliate plugins but at the time his team could not confidently recommend any of the existing solutions. They found most to be “unreliable
column3246:
and generally not a good fit.”

\n

“After a particularly painful support ticket where it was discovered that one of our customers had paid (or not paid) thousands of dollars to the wrong people due to a bug in their affiliate tracking plugin
column3247: we decided to do something about it
column3248:
” Williamson said.

\n

He worked in his spare time and late at night to develop AffiliateWP while supporting EDD and Restrict Content Pro during business hours. The product’s revenue now supports a full-time team of six people.

\n

“It humbles me to think that my little side project could go from an after-hours project to providing for the full time jobs of an entire team
column3249:
” Williamson said.

\n

AffiliateWP’s Business Model Helped it Grow Faster than EDD

\n

Easy Digital Downloads
column3251: is touted as having pioneered one of the most wildly successful business models in the WordPress ecosystem
column3252:
but AffiliateWP was not built on the same model. EDD offers a free base plugin with commercial add-ons available a la carte. AffiliateWP does not have an official free product and is not directly supported by commercial extensions.

\n

Pricing for the product starts at $49 and ranges up to $449
column3253:
with different packages that include varying levels of support and Professional add-ons.

\n

“Utilizing this business model is without any doubt one of reasons AffiliateWP accelerated at the rate it did
column3254: ” Williamson said. “This model has not only been lucrative for us
column3255:
I personally think it’s superior in many ways to other models common throughout the WordPress ecosystem.

\n

“I like it enough that we recently chose to migrate Restrict Content Pro to the same model
column3256: ” he said. “If I had the opportunity to start over with Easy Digital Downloads
column3257:
I would almost certainly opt to use the same model there as well instead of selling each add-on individually.”

\n

AffiliateWP’s total revenue for 2015 was $379
column3258: 078 and Williamson projects that figure to be in the neighborhood of $420
column3260:
000 for 2016.

\n

The fact that AffiliateWP is also available for free on GitHub has not compromised the product’s success. In fact
column3261:
Williamson believes it has only enhanced it. The open source plugin has received contributions from 49 different developers.

\n

“This is a stat I’m particularly proud of considering AffiliateWP is a commercial product
column3262: a category of WordPress plugins that tends to get very little development from anyone outside of the core development team of the product
column3263:
” Williamson said. “We chose to make AffiliateWP 100% open on GitHub with a public repository specifically to help facilitate contributions from other developers. I believe firmly that this was a good decision that has worked out quite well for us.”

\n

Williamson’s transparency about his plugin revenue serves as an inspiration to other entrepreneurs in the commercial plugin space. AffiliateWP’s success is an example of what’s possible in the WordPress product space with hard work

In this episode of WordPress Weekly
column3267: Marcus Couch and I discuss the news of the week
column3268:
including a big move for VersionPress as it transitions into an open source project. We provide an update on the development status of bbPress and BuddyPress. We also share details of a critical security vulnerability that was patched in a popular user role management plugin. Last but not least is Marcus’ plugin picks of the week.

Stories Discussed:

VersionPress Transitions Into a Free Open Source Project
Outdated and Vulnerable WordPress and Drupal Versions May Have Contributed to the Panama Papers Breach
BuddyPress 2.6 Development Kicks Off
column3269:
David Cavins to Lead Release
\nbbPress 2.6 Expected Later This Year
column3270:
Two Major Features Pushed Back to 2.7
WP REST API Team Aims for WordPress 4.7 for Merge Proposal
User Role Editor 4.25 Patches Critical Security Vulnerability
Europe Tops WordCamp Growth in 2015 with 70% Increase in Events

Plugins Picked By Marcus:

Query All The Post Types provides a quick and easy way to view a list of all the post types registered in a WordPress installation.

GoWorks Styler adds new buttons to the WordPress visual editor
column3271: allowing you to enhance posts and pages with custom colors
column3275:
and more.

Chronological Posts reverses the default post order throughout your site to be chronological instead of reverse-chronological.

Last year WordCamp London introduced “Wapuunk
column3280: igniting a new wapuu craze for WordCamps held in the Western hemisphere. The 2015 event had commemorative stickers printed along with a Wapuunk-embroidered scarf for attendees. Shortly thereafter
column3281:
nearly every WordCamp organization team began designing their own custom wapuu mascots.

\n

WordCamp London 2016 will take place this weekend at the London Metropolitan University. The event’s official wapuu will be printed on stickers and may be incorporated into other vintage London-inspired WordCamp swag.

\n

Wapuu collectors in attendance this weekend will want to arrive at the event early
column3282: as a limited edition R2-Wapuu has also been designed in honor of the WordCamp. UK-based designers Gemma Garner and Scott Evans collaborated on the R2-D2-inspired wapuu and printed a small batch of 100 stickers. Approximately 600 people are expected to attend this year’s event
column3283:
so only the lucky few who hunt down Garner or Evans will receive an R2-wapuu sticker. An .svg file of the design will be sent to the official wapuu archive on GitHub if you want to print your own.

\n

\n

WordCamp London 2016 will kick off in less than 48 hours. A film crew will be creating a documentary about this year’s event
column3284: bringing the camera behind the scenes to capture footage that doesn’t usually make it to WordPress.tv’s educational archive. The event is nearly sold out. Last minute WordCampers hoping to attend should purchase their tickets ASAP
column3285:
because there are only 45 spots remaining.

\n

Authorities have not yet identified the hacker behind the Panama Papers breach
column3287: nor have they isolated the exact attack vector. It is clear that Mossack Fonseca
column3288: the Panamanian law firm that protected the assets of the rich and powerful by setting up shell companies
column3289:
had employed a dangerously loose policy towards web security and communications.

\n

The firm ran its unencrypted emails through an outdated (2009) version of Microsoft’s Outlook Web Access. Outdated open source software running the frontend of the firm’s websites is also now suspected to have provided a vector for the compromise.

\n

In initial communications with German newspaper the Süddeutsche Zeitung (SZ)
column3290: an anonymous source offered the data with a few conditions
column3291:
saying that his/her life was in danger.

\n

“How much data are we talking about?” the SZ asked.

\n

“More than anything you have ever seen
column3292:
” the source said.

\n

The Panama Papers breach is the largest data leak in history by a wide margin
column3296:
000 shell companies exposed.

\n

Forbes has identified outdated WordPress and Drupal installations as security holes that may have led to the data leak.

\n

Forbes discovered the firm ran a three-month-old version of WordPress for its main site
column3300: its portal used by customers to access sensitive data was most likely run on a three-year-old version of Drupal
column3302: however. While looking at the site today
column3303: I found that the firm’s WordPress-powered site is currently running on version 4.1 (released in December 2014)
column3304: based on its version of autosave.js
column3305:
which is identical to the autosave.js file shipped in 4.1. Since that time WordPress has had numerous critical security updates.

\n

The main site is also loading a number of outdated scripts and plugins. Its active theme is a three-year-old version of Twenty Eleven (1.5)
column3306:
which oddly resides in a directory labeled for /twentyten/.

\n

The Mossack Fonseca client portal changelog.txt file is public
column3307: showing that its Drupal installation hasn’t been updated for three years. Since the release of version 7.23
column3308: the software has received 25 security updates
column3309: which means that the version it is running includes highly critical known vulnerabilities that could have given the hacker access to the server. This includes a 2014 SQL injection vulnerability known in the Drupal community as “Drupalgeddon
column3310:
” which affected every site running Drupal 7.31 or below.

\n

Investigators have not confirmed if the open source software vulnerabilities were used to access the data
column3311:
but it is certainly plausible given the severity of the vulnerabilities in both older versions of WordPress and Drupal.

\n

“They seem to have been caught in a time warp
column3313: a computer security expert from Surrey University
column3314:
told WIRED UK. “If I were a client of theirs I’d be very concerned that they were communicating using such outdated technology.”

\n

If these open source software vulnerabilities provided the access point for this massive leak
column3315: then this company’s global fiasco was entirely preventable. Although many people welcome the uncovering of corruption and dirty money transactions of famous people and world leaders
column3316: the reality is that these kinds of exploits can also be carried out on well-meaning organizations that exist to protect people’s health records
column3318:
and other sensitive information.

\n

This leak is not a measure of open source software’s reliability but rather underscores how low a priority some companies place on their tech departments and web security. With the rampant software vulnerabilities in this age
column3319:
not updating software for years constitutes abject neglect of customers.

\n

The bottom line is that software needs to be updated. This kind of routine maintenance is as foundational to a company’s business as brushing teeth or showering is for one’s health. Law firms and companies with such a lax approach to security are either ignorant or unwilling to spend the money to maintain technology that they don’t fully understand. The Panama Papers serve as a reminder that having a competent
column3320:
skilled tech department is critical for any company that deals in sensitive information.

\n

Borek Bernard and Jan Voráček
column3323: announced that they’re transitioning the plugin into a free
column3324: open source project hosted on GitHub. In addition
column3326:
the first version released under the new model.

\n

Open Source Is the Way Forward

\n

In a post on the product’s site
column3327:
Bernard explains that the only way for the project to be successful is to open up development to the public.

\n

“Towards the end of 2015
column3328: we started feeling it was the right time to convert the project to a fully open-sourced one
column3329:
” he said.

\n

“The project started to be in good shape – had a clear direction set
column3330: most of the technical groundwork was laid
column3331: and we moved to GitHub. While we had most of WordPress core covered pretty well
column3332:
there was still this huge ecosystem of WordPress plugins and themes that could cause trouble to VersionPress in millions of different ways.

\n

“In the long run
column3333: the project had to turn into OSS should it be successful
column3336: we met investors who understood this and supported our vision
column3337:
” Bernard said.

\n

The transition involved quite a bit of work migrating from Bitbucket and JIRA to GitHub. Old Wiki documents and other assets were migrated as well. In addition to the migration
column3338: old issues were translated to English and Daniel Bachhuber
column3339:
who maintains the WP-CLI project audited the code. The project’s website also received a facelift.

\n

By transitioning to a public development model
column3340:
Bernard hopes to tap into new resources to solve challenging problems.

\n

“We’ll need your bright minds to solve some of the more difficult issues later this year
column3341: like how to integrate with complex plugins with custom DB structures
column3345:
the plugin will not be hosted in the WordPress plugin directory anytime soon.

\n

“It stays in the ‘Early Access’ phase where it works well in certain scenarios but there are still many incompatible plugins
column3347: ” Bernard said. “There’s no magic solution to this
column3349:
and more and more plugins and scenarios will be supported over time.”

\n

Early Access Program Discontinued

\n

The Early Access Program
column3350: which provided initial funding to develop VersionPress beyond its crowdfunding campaign
column3351:
is being discontinued.

\n

“EAP was of great help but couldn’t really fund the project
column3353: ” Bernard told the Tavern. While the team doesn’t have a replacement for the revenue provided by EAP
column3354:
Bernard plans to build exceptional value around the core of VersionPress which he says will remain free forever.

\n

How to Follow the Project

\n

VersionPress 3.0 beta marks the first major release in more than five months. It includes bug fixes and a number of enhancements. You can follow the project’s progress on GitHub where you can also receive support
column3356:
and find access to their Gitter room for real-time communication. Pull requests from the community are welcomed.

\n

Keeping up and monitoring the progress of WordCamps in and around your area is now a lot easier thanks to a new WordCamp Application status page. The page indicates a WordCamp’s city
column3361:
and the last time it was updated.

\nWordCamp Central Application Status Tracking\n

The application status page is the result of efforts by Ian Dunn and Konstantin Kovshenin who are improving the sites and tools organizers use to coordinate events. On the Make WordPress Community blog
column3362:
Andrea Middleton explains the changes and what deputies can expect.

\n

Deputies are WordCamp Central volunteers who respond to WordCamp/meetup applications
column3364:
and mentor organizers. They work behind the scenes to ensure events are run smoothly and adhere to the WordPress Foundation’s guidelines.

\n

It’s interesting to see how WordPress is helping the team organize submissions and streamlining the process. According to Middleton
column3365:
incoming applications automatically create draft listings on WordCamp Central and receive the status “Needs Vetting.”

\nWordCamp Central Application Processing\n

As the team moves through the process of vetting
column3370:
deputies make notes in the post editor which are attached to the application. The site makes use of custom post statuses which are applied based on the application’s progress. It also adds accountability by saving a change log to each WordCamp listing that indicates when the status is changed and who changed it.

\n

While this information is specific to those who work with WordCamp organizers
column3371:
it provides a glimpse into the tools and processes volunteers use to coordinate events. It’s also a neat look into how handy custom post statuses are.

\n

With all of the improvements to the backend
column3372: WordCamp and event organizers should experience fewer delays in response times. If you’re a deputy or frequent browser of WordCamp Central and have a suggestion or request to improve the site
column3373:
you can share it by leaving a comment on the announcement post.

\n

By the way
column3374: community deputies are an excellent way to contribute to the WordPress project without knowing how to code. To learn more about what deputies do and how you can join the program
column3376:

Today GitHub announced a new feature that allows project owners to block abusive users from public repositories. Users who are blocked will no longer be able to open or comment on issues or pull requests
column3381:
nor will they will not be able to add or edit any of the project’s wiki pages. Blocked users are also prevented from forking any of the organization’s repositories. Blocking goes beyond a simple warning and is a serious capability for project owners to use at their discretion.

\n

\n

Many WordPress plugin authors opt to host their work on GitHub because of the burden of support on WordPress.org. When entitled users have unreasonably high expectations of the free support forum
column3382: they sometimes resort to abuse to try to force developers to assist them. At the very least
column3383:
many abuse the star rating system and use it to communicate disappointment.

\n

While GitHub caters to a different type of user (usually developers)
column3384:
the site is not immune to abusive users. The new blocking capabilities were added to help project owners encourage positive contributions. One foul user who abuses contributors can poison the well and rob a team of its forward momentum.

\n

Open source projects often bring together a surprisingly varied array of personalities with differing opinions that can result in heated debates. On occasion
column3385: these kinds of conversations can devolve into ad hominem attacks and other unsavory comments. The definition of abuse will vary from project to project
column3386: but a definition in the project’s contributing file may help for the sake of transparency when blocking users. A record of which users have been blocked is added to the organization’s audit log
column3387:
so this information is open and available to project contributors.

\n

During the 2015 State of the Word address
column3389: Matt Mullenweg shared a few stats that demonstrate the growth of the global WordPress community. A total of 89 WordCamps with 21
column3390:
000 attendees were held across 34 countries in 2015.

\n

This week WordPress community organizer Andrea Middleton published a more thorough breakdown of 2015 stats. She noted that while WordCamps have been steadily growing over the past five years
column3391: the increase is due to more numerous
column3392: smaller events. This kind of growth seems more in line with the intended purpose of WordCamps. Although a few camps stand out as large international events
column3393:
most are meant to be low-key gatherings that bring together local communities.

\n

“We saw a huge jump in WordCamps held in Europe this year — from 17 in 2014 to 29 in 2015
column3394:
” Middleton said. “And a whopping 18 WordPress communities organized their very first WordCamp last year.”

\n

In 9 months
column3395:
the Italian #WordPress community grew from 0 to 10 meetups and a WordCamp. Standing ovations. #WCTRN pic.twitter.com/mgXpFV22GS

\n

— Petya Raykovska (@petyeah) April 2
column3396:
2016

\n

\n

With a 70% increase in European WordCamp events
column3397:
it no surprise that WordCamp Europe 2016 had to expand its attendee capacity to 2200. The event will be the largest WordCamp to date.

\n

In 2015
column3398:
many of the largest WordCamps were held in the US but Europe and Japan also have events ranking in the top five. The ten largest WordCamps (based on number of tickets sold) in 2015 were as follows:

  • WordCamp US
  • WordCamp Tokyo
  • WordCamp Europe
  • WordCamp Kansai
  • WordCamp NYC
  • WordCamp London
  • WordCamp Miami
  • WordCamp Atlanta
  • WordCamp Orlando

The overall number of tickets sold for WordCamps worldwide is also steadily rising
column3401:
000 in 2015.

\n

\n

As the global WordPress community continues to expand
column3402: the burden on WordCamp Central grows. Overseeing WordCamps and meetups is a full time job. In 2014
column3403:
the WordPress Community Team established a deputies program to share the load and expanded the number of volunteers to 30 during 2015.

\n

In the first quarter report for 2016
column3404: Middleton reported that the community team helped facilitate nine WordCamps with a total of nearly 4
column3405:
500 tickets sold. WordCamp Central also signed Pantheon and GoDaddy as global sponsors.

\n

There are already 24 WordCamps on the calendar for the April-June period and 14 more scheduled for the remaining quarters. Middleton also reported that 31 additional WordCamps have been approved are now in the pipeline at the pre-planning stage.

\n

“With WordCamp applications coming in at an average rate of 13 per month
column3406: it’s very likely that we’ll see more than 100 WordCamps in 2016

Hello WordPress users! Version 5.2 of the WordPress for Android app is now available in the Google Play Store.

In version 5.2
column3409: you may notice a difference in font in the app: we replaced the Open Sans font in the UI with Roboto
column3410: the default Android font. For those with a sharp eye
column3411: you also might notice that we’re still using the Merriweather font for user-generated content
column3412: like reader comments and the content in your post editor. (For the typographically curious
column3413:
take a look at the WordPress.com Design Handbook.)

Version 5.2 also comes with an updated Account Settings screen. You can change your email address
column3415:
and web address in your app:

\n
    \n
  • Email address: This is your primary email address associated with your account
column3416: which is not publicly displayed. If you update your email address
column3417:
you will receive an email to confirm it.
  • Primary site: Your primary site is typically the one you most commonly use. You can update your primary site from a popover display with a list of all of your sites.
  • Web address: This is the URL that is shown publicly when you comment on blogs.

    • We also dropped the “auto-share” and “post signature” settings from this screen.

    We’re working hard on new features for the next versions
column3418:
and you can track development progress for the next version by visiting our 5.3 milestone on GitHub.

\n

Thank you

\n

@aforcier

Vladimir Garagulya
column3429: developer of the User Role Editor has patched a critical security vulnerability. User Role Editor is used to edit
column3431:
and create user roles and capabilities and is active on more than 300K sites.

\nUser Role Editor Interface\n

User Role Editor 4.24 and below allows any registered user to gain administrator access. Wordfence
column3432:
a popular security plugin for WordPress has more details and explains why the plugin was vulnerable:

\n

The author was checking if users have access to edit another user using the ‘current_user_can’ function and checking for the ‘edit_user’ (without an ‘s’ on the end) capability on a specific user ID. A user can edit themselves
column3433:
and so sending data to the plugin that supplies the current user’s ID to this access check would bypass the check.

\n

Users should immediately upgrade to 4.25 to protect sites from this vulnerability.

\n

The WP REST API team released version 2.0 beta 13 of the feature plugin today. This release includes a couple of breaking changes
column3436:
and many other fixes and improvements.

\n

Developers who use the plugin in their projects can expect it to follow a more stable release cycle in the future
column3437: as beta 13 marks the last of the breaking changes. According to project lead Ryan McCue
column3438:
the team plans to add new features to minor releases in the 2.x series and bugfix releases in the 2.0.x series.

\n

“Along these lines
column3439: we’re going to release a 2.0 final version in the coming months
column3440:
” McCue said. “This will be a completely stable release with guaranteed backwards compatibility for the foreseeable future. This backwards compatibility ensures that your sites can remain up-to-date with minimal maintenance or issues with upgrading.”

\n

The beta release post also included an updated roadmap for the project. The team is not planning to put forward part two of their merge proposal
column3441: which would add the core endpoints
column3442:
for WordPress 4.6. They will be holding off until WordPress 4.7 in hopes of gaining more users with the stable 2.0 release.

\n

We believe endpoints for the main WordPress objects (posts
column3446: and taxonomies) are not enough to garner the support needed for the proposal to be accepted. Our hope is that with a stable version 2.0 release
column3447: we will attract our community members that have been waiting for the endpoints to be available in core
column3448:
and submit a merge proposal for the WordPress 4.7 release cycle.

\n

Although the greater WordPress development community is excited about the potential of the REST API
column3449: the contributor base remains relatively small and spread thin for the task of keeping pace with core. McCue
column3450: speaking on behalf of the team
column3451:
said they are looking to get more help from WordPress core component maintainers as well as outside developers.

\n

“Moving forward
column3452: the API team sees our role as advisory over the API itself
column3453: with the API treated as an integral part of the component rather than maintained by a separate team
column3454: ” McCue said. “We’re also going to continue to work on our feature plugins (metadata
column3458:
and are looking for help on these as well.”

\n

With the plugin approaching its 2.0 final version on a more stable path
column3459: it is a good time for new developers to get involved. The WP REST API team plans to allocate more time for mentoring and helping developers use the API. If you want to get involved
column3460:
jump in on the comments of the release post or join the team in the #core-restapi Slack channel.

\n

Last month WordPress contributors approved accessibility coding standards for the core handbook. All new and updated code will need to conform with WCAG 2.0 level AA guidelines.

With WordPress core moving firmly in the direction of accessibility
column3462: its new guidelines set the bar for themes
column3464: and websites built on top of the platform. Text and background contrast
column3466: is one of the easiest places to get started. WCAG 2.0 color requirements recommend a contrast ratio of 4.5 for small text or 3 for large text
column3467:
which is 24px or 18px bold.

\n

Color Safe is a handy web app that helps designers select color combinations that will meet WCAG 2.0 guidelines for those with different visual capabilities. You enter the background color
column3470:
and the tool generates a palette of safe options for your text color.

\n

\n

The palette can be sorted by general color groups and selections can be previewed at the top of the screen. By default
column3471: the generator uses AA level guidelines. If you’re building for a company or government website that requires AAA specifications
column3472:
you can select it from the dropdown and all colors generated in the palette will be in compliance.

Color Safe was built by Salesforce UX engineer Donielle Berg and product designer Adrian Rapp to help designers include accessibility as part of the design process. The tool takes the guesswork out of complying with WCAG guidelines and makes it easy to visually explore accessible color combinations.

There’s a lot of great WordPress content published in the community but not all of it is featured on the Tavern. This post is an assortment of items related to WordPress that caught my eye but didn’t make it into a full post.

Jen Mylo Moves on From Automattic

Jen Mylo
column3475: announced she has left her position at Automattic after eight years to pursue other opportunities. Normally
column3476:
people switching or leaving jobs isn’t news but Mylo is an exception to the rule because of the impact she’s had on the WordPress project and community over those eight years.

\n

From leading the effort to redesign the WordPress 2.7 “Coltrane” backend which was code-named Crazyhorse
column3477: to helping WordCamp organizers behind the scenes
column3478:
to the Kim Parsell travel scholarship. She also facilitated and helped many WordPress lead developers.

Thanks Jen for everything you’ve done and contributed to the WordPress project and its community. I wish and hope for the best for you in your future endeavors.

Generous in Spirit

Carrie Dils reminds us that the WordPress community is generous of spirit. If you haven’t experienced it yet
column3479:
get in touch with her and she’ll introduce you.

\n

The #WordPress community is so generous of spirit. If you feel disconnected from it and want to be a part
column3480:
message me & I\'ll introduce you.

\n

— carrie dils (@cdils) March 31
column3481:
2016

How to Protect a GPL Licensed Plugin from Being Copied

There’s a post on the Advanced WordPress Facebook group that asks
column3482:
what are the best ways to protect a GPL licensed plugin from being copied? The thread has more than a dozen responses with many explaining that copying is at the core of the license. The simple answer is that you don’t.

Comparison: Working from Home vs In an Office

The Onion compares what it’s like to work from home as opposed to working in an office. I think the humorous comparisons ring true for many.

Working From Home Compared to Working In an Office

WordPress 4.5 Field Guide

Everything you need to know to prepare for WordPress 4.5 is in the field guide. Thanks to Aaron Jorbin for putting the guide together as it’s a great resource for those not able to keep up with development.

Jumboji

The only thing better than emoji in core is jumbo emoji. Thankfully
column3483:
there’s a plugin available that turns emoji into almost larger than life emoji.

\n

I am delighted to unveil Big Emoji Comments (Jumboji) for WordPress: https://t.co/AcEBzmvjCV pic.twitter.com/3g6Ii8AsUg

\n

— george ﬆephanis (@daljo628) March 24
column3484:
2016

Gianuu or Italian Wapuu!

In what is a traditional part of this series
column3485: I end each issue by featuring a Wapuu design. For those who don’t know
column3486: Wapuu is the unofficial mascot of the WordPress project. Gianduu is the official mascot of WordCamp Torino 2016. Gianduu is a mix between Gianuja
column3487: a famous carnival mask and Gianduiotto
column3488:
a Turin confectionery tradition.

\nGianduu\n

That’s it for issue six. If you recently discovered a cool resource or post related to WordPress
column3489:
please share it with us in the comments.

01 Apr 2016 22:23:36 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Jeff Chandler";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:15;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:" ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:73:"WPTavern: Features-as-Plugins First Transitions Into Features-as-Projects";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"http://wptavern.com/?p=53097";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:83:"http://wptavern.com/features-as-plugins-first-transitions-into-features-as-projects";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:7058:"photo credit: Office Pranks – (license)

Last year
column3491: I identified key factors that suggested the features-as-plugins first model was falling apart. A lack of communication
column3494:
and synchronized development between plugins on Github and WordPress.org were some of the contributing factors highlighted.

Features-as-Projects

WordPress lead developer Helen Hou-Sandí has outlined a new strategy for the model transitioning from a features-as-plugins approach to features-as-projects.

“Thinking of features as plugins has strapped us in a number of ways
column3495: in large part because the ‘plugin’ part implies a functional project from the start
column3497: experienced and newer contributors alike set their initial goal to be some sort of functional plugin. As a result
column3498: by the time something is being proposed in whatever forum
column3499:
there’s been a fair amount of effort spent – and personal attachment developed – for something that might be headed in the wrong direction. Changing direction at that point is very demoralizing and has led to burn out and less participation.”

A New Page for Featured Projects

Feature projects are listed on a new page which includes a brief explanation of the problems being solved. Active projects include WordPress NUX which aims to remove barriers to entry and Font Natively which switches to system fonts to load faster and provide a more native experience.

Anyone can suggest a feature project but its mission statement must clearly address what problem it’s trying to solve
column3501:
and how it fits into WordPress’ core philosophies and objective. The new page also serves as a roadmap for future feature projects.

\n

By changing their approach
column3502:
the core team hopes to achieve the following individual goals.

\n
    \n
  • To attract and retain a greater range of skill sets in contributors
column3503:
for example through being able to more thoroughly engage designers in early stages.
  • Implementing methods of collecting usage information and other data.
  • Supporting feature projects with resources for user testing and more structured feedback.
  • Advance both contributor and general community knowledge around product design and development.

    • Beginning Tuesday
column3507: bi-weekly meetings will be held where people can propose and discuss feature projects. These meetings are also where project leaders can ask for help
column3509:
and maintain direction.

\n

Design and Discovery First

\n

Perhaps one of the most important changes in the process is the focus on discovery and design first. Instead of testing features after they’re developed
column3510:
this plan focuses on gathering testing and usage data from users before technical implementation occurs.

\n

“Feature design and development should come from interviews with users
column3515:
” Hou-Sandí said.

\n

“Proper discovery will allow for testing long before functional development begins using low-fidelity storyboards and walking through potential concepts with users
column3516:
both verbally and visually. Projects should check in at a meeting when discovery results are available and continue to check in through the design process.”

\n

Even though the discovery and design phase may not lead to a full-fledged feature in core
column3517:
the process should help discover pain points along the way which can translate into other improvements.

\n

Iterating is Not Just For Software

\n

The new model incorporates many of the suggestions by WordPress lead developer
column3518:
Ryan Boren from 2014.

  • Be present and up-to-date in the plugin directory.
  • Be as ready to go on mobile as they are on desktop.
  • Have visual records for major flows through all new interfaces on all devices.
  • Have mature UI that isn’t going to derail the release train.
  • Have a history of posting weekly updates to make/core.
  • Have a history of regular plugin directory updates.
  • Have a testing audience.
  • Publish a merge consideration post on make/core complete with visual records and other diligence.
  • Exist for at least one release cycle. Plugins created at the beginning of a release cycle should not be considered for merge until the next release.

It also focuses on establishing a direction for a project early on instead of people aimlessly developing it to see where it goes. It’s worth noting that Boren supports the changes to the model.

Early feedback suggests this is a great move. Michelle Schulp
column3520:
had this to say about the changes:

\n

Love this
column3521: not only because it a) treats WordPress more like an actual product where decisions on features should be tested and vetted before they’re built
column3522: and b) validates the design and discovery process as ‘important to WordPress’ and saves a ton of unnecessary dev time
column3523:
but also c) will help encourage those with other important talents like design/ux/ui/user testing (but not core-level development skills) to contribute.

\n

Although I suggested renaming feature plugins to feature experiments
column3524:
feature projects is pretty good name. It’s nice to see the model evolve and address many of the problems I outlined in 2015. I encourage you to read the full post and let us know what you think of the changes.

\n

Two Major Features Pushed Back to 2.7\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"http://wptavern.com/?p=53134\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:94:\"http://wptavern.com/bbpress-2-6-expected-later-this-year-two-major-features-pushed-back-to-2-7\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1961:\"

There hasn’t been a lot of news about bbPress lately but earlier this week on the project’s development blog
column3527:
John James Jacoby provided a status update on the progress of 2.6 and what to expect for 2.7.

\n

According to the post
column3528: the team has worked hard on 2.6 since 2.5’s release in 2013. Unfortunately
column3529:
two highly anticipated features that were expected to be in 2.6 have been pushed back to 2.7. Jacoby explains why:

\n

Stephen and I have been steadily improving and readying the next major version (2.6) ever since releasing 2.5.0
column3530: and while many huge features and neat little improvements have already landed in the development version
column3531:
there are 2 features that will likely get bumped to 2.7 so we can call 2.6 done:

  • bbPress as Post Comments
  • Forums as Taxonomies

These two features are fully architected and planned
column3532:
but do not have enough progress in code for them to hold up the release of 2.6.

\n

Users can expect to see betas and release candidates of bbPress 2.6 in the coming weeks. Jacoby notes that development on 2.7 will exclusively focus on the two missing features.

\n

As someone who is waiting on the bbPress as Post Comments feature before diving into bbPress
column3533: I’m disappointed. I’m grateful for the time and effort Jacoby
column3535: and others put into the project but considering its release history
column3536:
it may be another 1-2 years before 2.7 is a reality. I don’t know if I can wait that long.

\n

David Cavins to Lead Release\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:28:\"http://wptavern.com/?p=53003\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:85:\"http://wptavern.com/buddypress-2-6-development-kicks-off-david-cavins-to-lead-release\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3909:\"

\n

Development on BuddyPress 2.6 began this week with a meeting to set the schedule and scope for the release. The BuddyPress project recently moved to adopt release leads as part of the core development process.

\n

“The release lead gets a sense at the beginning of the dev cycle what he/she would like to accomplish
column3539: as well as what others want and are willing to contribute
column3540: ” Boone Gorges said during last week’s development meeting. “Within those parameters
column3541:
there is likely lots of room for the lead to make decisions about what the focus should be.”

\n

David Cavins was named release lead for the upcoming 2.6 release and @mercime will be on deck for 2.7. During this week’s meeting
column3542:
Cavins set a schedule for 2.6:

  • Beta: May 25
  • RC1: June 8
  • Official Release: June 15

Cavins said that 2.6 will focus on performance and UI polish
column3543:
as many of the tickets filed for the milestone fall into those general categories. Contributors chimed in during the meeting to express interest in working on specific goals and tickets:

  • A new API to manage single items navigation (#6534)
  • Incrementor-based caching for ID queries (#6643)
  • Explore implementing Behat to add a functional testing capability to the project
  • Extend BuddyPress’ use of caching to group memberships
  • Framework for bulk data handling after updates (#6841)

Cavins is also organizing a few “BuddyPress Work Parties” early in the release cycle where contributors can get together to collaborate on tickets
column3546:
and answering support questions.

\n

In addition to the new release leads concept
column3547: the BuddyPress core team is also considering implementing component maintainers
column3548:
similar to the way WordPress core is organized.

\n

“It gives newcomers a sense of where to look if they have questions about a part of BP
column3549: or want to get involved in contributing
column3550: ” Gorges said. “It also creates a sense of ownership for people who are already doing the practical work of triaging certain kinds of tickets
column3551:
and encourages people to step up and take a role of responsibility.”

\n

BuddyPress project lead John James Jacoby said that component maintainers has been one of his personal leadership goals for BuddyPress for a long time
column3552:
with individuals and eventually teams “owning” components to make them shine.

\n

“The main reasons to do it are empowering people to make decisions
column3553: and to elevate everyone’s contributions by promoting within and creating goals for contributors to graduate to
column3555:
” Jacoby said.

\n

Specific maintainers and/or teams have not yet been identified but the core team is working towards making this more official to streamline contributions.

\n

Welcome to the Post Status Draft podcast
column3559:
and via RSS for your favorite podcatcher. Post Status Draft is hosted by Joe Hoyle — the CTO of Human Made — and Brian Krogsgard.

\n

Today
column3560: we answer questions from Post Status community members
column3561: who asked us all sorts of stuff on the Post Status Ask page. If you’d like to ask a question
column3562:
be sure to go there and we’ll see if we can answer it on a future show.

https://audio.simplecast.com/34442.mp3

Direct Download

Questions & Links

We answered the following questions:

Why WordPress?

In a survey I did before my PressNomics talk
column3563:
the top answer for what’s important to people in regards to the WordPress world was the quality of the community. WordPress’ ubiquity — powering 26% of the web — helps too.

\n

What is the biggest mistake you made learning WordPress? (Or
column3564:
what would you do differently?)

\n

Joe and I each shared what we tend to do wrong when learning new things. We are fully on opposite ends of the spectrum. Recommended link: Just Build Websites. Also
column3565: my post on learning WordPresss holds up pretty well
column3566:
considering I wrote it in 2014.

\n

Why did a lot of web and WordPress people get upset about the Mandrill pricing changes
column3567:
when we want people to value the work we’re doing ourselves?

\n

We discuss what made Mandrill’s pricing changes controversial
column3568: and why we think some level of “outcry” is understandable here. Basically
column3569: Mandrill isn’t differentiated enough to warrant the new pricing
column3571: it’s obviously their right to change their pricing and structure
column3572:
and the questioner has a valid point in how we value other services versus our own.

\n

The WordPress REST API clearly has the attention of savvy WordPress developers
column3573:
but will it really change WordPress as we know it?

\n

It’s hard to know exactly how the REST API will change WordPress. It partly depends on how extensive the core inclusion of the API is. But at a minimum
column3574:
the WordPress REST API plugin will be maintained and offer a new way of interacting with WordPress for anyone that wants to do so. And efforts into learning the API will definitely be transferable to using other REST APIs on the web.

\n

Why isn’t the WordPress importer being worked on more intensively?

\n

Good question! We talk about the state of the importer
column3575: some other options like WP Migrate DB Pro
column3577:
and WP CLI. We also discuss how to get involved with open source development.

\n

Should taxonomies have the same feature capabilities as posts in the future?

\n

There’s been a lot of interesting work on taxonomies in the last several releases
column3578: and you can read more about some of that and find links going back from my release post for WordPress 4.4. However
column3579: we think taxonomies and posts should be different. With the introduction of term meta
column3580: it is more important to consider architectural choices well in advance. Finally
column3581:
the Fields API will be interesting in how it affects customizing term edit screens.

\n

How should I use my own domains with Multisite?

\n

This turned interesting! Fortunately
column3582: Multisite component maintainer Jeremy Felt came through while we were on the show to point us to tickets that were merged in WordPress 3.9 for enabling simpler domain mapping
column3584: when a better UI was introduced. So
column3586:
it’s much easier to use a custom domain in a network — within the existing WordPress Multisite options interface — versus using a tool like Mercator.

\n
\n

In addition to these questions
column3587: we also banter on about some other things and answer a few less serious questions we got from funny listeners. And at the end
column3588:
I make a pretty big announcement…

\n
\n

Version 3.1.10 of the Akismet plugin for WordPress is now available.

This update fixes a bug that could cause comments caught as spam to end up in the Pending queue. It also fixes the History entries for comments caught by WordPress’s built-in Comment Blacklist in WordPress 4.4 or later.

Version 3.1.10 is confirmed compatible with WordPress 4.5
column3596: visit the Updates page of your WordPress dashboard and follow the instructions. If you need to download the plugin zip file directly
column3597:
links to all versions are available in the WordPress plugins directory.

Jetpack 3.9.5 was released yesterday with compatibilities for the upcoming WordPress 4.5 release and a handful of enhancements/bug fixes. Shortly after issuing the routine maintenance update
column3599: the Jetpack team began receiving reports of random
column3600:
unwanted videos being added to the comments of posts. Any number string in the comments was automatically converted into a Vimeo video.

\n

No
column3601: this bug was not an April Fool’s Day prank
column3602: although it seemed like it. As a temporary fix
column3603:
support representatives recommended that users deactivate the Shortcode Embeds module.

\n

We’re aware of an issue with numbers in comments embedding random Vimeo videos and are working to get 3.9.6 out as a fix ASAP.

\n

— Jetpack (@jetpack) March 31
column3604:
2016

\n

\n

The Jetpack team scrambled to fix the rather humorous and annoying bug
column3605:
which had been introduced while fixing another Vimeo bug. A few hours later they shipped 3.9.6 on the heels of the maintenance release. Users who updated to 3.9.5 right away will need to update again in order to avoid running into this bug.

\n

01 Apr 2016 04:43:39 +0000";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}s:32:"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/";a:1:{s:7:"creator";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:13:"Sarah Gooding";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}}}}i:21;a:6:{s:4:"data";s:13:" ";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:2:{s:0:"";a:5:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:81:"WPTavern: WordPress.org UX Research Begins as Part of Long-Term Plan for Redesign";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"guid";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:28:"http://wptavern.com/?p=53042";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:91:"http://wptavern.com/wordpress-org-ux-research-begins-as-part-of-long-term-plan-for-redesign";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:0:"";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:0;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:3995:"photo credit: Lukasz Kowalewski

WordPress.org is second only to WordPress.com in Google search results for “WordPress
column3610: visitors to WordPress.org land on an outdated website that doesn’t accurately represent the vibrance of the WordPress project and its strong community. As the face of the open source project
column3611:
WordPress.org is in desperate need of a redesign.

\n

Designer Hugo Baeta is currently gathering feedback on the user experience of the site as part of a long-term plan for its improvement. WordPress.org is a slow-moving machine when it comes to updates and design changes
column3612:
but Baeta’s research is a solid first step towards action.

\n

“As we take on efforts of documenting and creating more polished and art directed design foundations for the WordPress project as a whole
column3613: the .org sites need to get some love as well
column3614:
” Baeta said.

\n

He posted results of a lengthy 55-question survey
column3615: summarizing anonymous feedback from 32 of WordPress’ most active contributors – project leads
column3617:
and highly active community members. The survey asked open-ended questions to encourage honest feedback on the site’s biggest pain-points.

\n

“This survey will help us get a better idea of the direction we need to go on a long-term plan to make improvements to WordPress.org
column3618: building a more solid and thought-out foundation so the community can grow and thrive for years to come
column3620: the primary reason they visit WordPress.org is to contribute to WordPress. Nearly all agreed that the design feels tired
column3625: that most respondents rarely (if ever) visit the WordPress download page
column3629:
the survey’s participants find the current design to be inconsistent and confusing to navigate unless you are an insider. Several responses communicated frustration that the site isn’t 100% WordPress and that its underlying code prevents it from being easily updated.

\n

Survey participants offered both sharp criticism and constructive feedback. If you have the time and inclination
column3630:
the results are worth a read.

\n

WordPress.org serves two different types of users: contributors and the millions of people who use and the software. Baeta did not indicate his next step in the UX research
column3631:
but it would be worthwhile to sample some first time visitors and users who frequent the pages that contributors don’t often visit.

\n

While open source software websites aren’t usually known for their cutting edge designs
column3632: many inspirational examples can be found at BeautifulOpen.com. Browsing that catalogue
column3633: it’s clear that WordPress.org could greatly benefit from a brighter
column3634:
more user-friendly design.

\n

Companies like Wix and Weebly
column3636: could never get away with having websites that don’t demonstrate the quality of their products. If WordPress is going to continue to grow past its current 26% market share
column3637:
the project’s website should reflect its reputation of being easy-to-use software for creating beautiful websites.

\n
